Quantum vere novo viridis se subicit alnus‘Gallus for
                                whom my love grows from hour to hour even as the green alder-tree
                                shoots up in the early spring.’;

Sed longe sequere et vestigia semper adora‘Live then,
                                I pray, yet rival not the divine Aeneid, but follow it from afar,
                                and ever reverence its track.’ Thebaid xii. 816.;

Atque humiles habitare casas, et figere cervos‘O that
                                it would but please you to dwell with me among the “homely slighted”
                                fields and lowly cottages, and to shoot the deer.’;

Plura domum tardis decedere plaustra iuvencis‘There is
                                no other land of plain from which you will see more wains wending
                                their way home with the lagging steers.’ ii. 205–206.;

Visa sub obscurum noctis‘A voice too was heard by many
                                through the silent groves, speaking a mighty sound, and ghosts,
                                wondrous pale, were seen in the dusk.’;

Per noctem resonare lupis ululantibus urbes‘And dogs
                                of ill omen and dire birds gave signs’—‘and mountain-built cities
                                echoed through the night with the howl of wolves.’;

div.p:
In this passage we note (1) Virgil’s relation to the earlier poem of
                       Naevius, who had sketched the outline of the scene which is here filled up;
                       and also the reproduction of the diction of Ennius in the passage—

